\begin{abstract}
We propose a method for interpretable neural rule learning in the Synthetic PolyRule Reasoning (SPR) task, which requires classification based on latent poly-factor rules. Existing neural and symbolic approaches either lack interpretability or rely on post-hoc methods that do not provide explicit rule representations. Our model is designed to learn and represent these rules in a human-readable format. We present experiments on the SPR\_BENCH dataset, focusing on classification accuracy and interpretable rule extraction. Results indicate that, while classification F1 scores approach 0.80, the learned rules capture partial dependencies underlying the task. We highlight trade-offs between performance and transparency, as well as potential overfitting when rule complexity is high.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
Practical applications of deep learning often involve complex reasoning and decision-making, where interpretability is critical \citep{goodfellow2016deep}. Neural rule learning aims to make learning models more transparent by discovering interpretable rule structures \citep{dong2019neurallm}. However, existing methods frequently rely on opaque high-dimensional embeddings \citep{barbiero2023interpretablenc}, or employ post-hoc explanation methods that can be unreliable in representing actual decision mechanisms \citep{hooshyar2024problemsws}. We address the Synthetic PolyRule Reasoning (SPR) task, where classification requires understanding symbol sequences governed by multiple latent factors. We investigate whether it is feasible for a neural system to learn these rules explicitly, evaluating both performance and interpretability.

\section{Related Work}
Neural-symbolic systems combine sub-symbolic processing with discrete rule structures, allowing models to perform logical inference while retaining flexibility \citep{liu2024neuralsymbolicro}. Symbolic reasoning approaches, such as building explicit rule structures, promote interpretability but may sacrifice generalization \citep{barbiero2023interpretablenc}. Benchmark tasks like KOR-Bench \citep{ma2024korbenchbl} and similar resources offer evaluations of rule-based reasoning in controlled datasets. In addition, supervised rule-based classifiers provide readable rules \citep{heider2020suprbas}, though neural networks typically incorporate rules only implicitly. Our approach aims to integrate techniques from these lines of work and provide both clarity in rule representation and competitive performance.

\section{Method}
We adopt a hybrid framework that combines a character-level encoder with a rule-based layer to produce explicit rules. A standard bi-directional recurrent encoder (or variant) transforms character sequences into hidden representations. In parallel, a lightweight linear rule extractor learns token-level importance weights that can be interpreted as class-specific triggers. The final classification logit is the ensemble average of these two branches. Training uses cross-entropy loss plus a regularization term to encourage sparse and interpretable rule weights. We rely on the Adam optimizer \citep{kingma2014adamam} and early stopping based on validation F1.

\section{Experiments}
We use the SPR\_BENCH dataset for training, validation, and testing, following the official splits. Our baseline is a Char-BiLSTM classifier trained on the same data. Its performance on the test set yields an F1 around 0.797. A sample confusion matrix is shown in Figure~\ref{fig:baseline_confmat}, revealing balanced misclassifications. We also compare different learning rates (Figure~\ref{fig:baseline_valf1}), observing that all converge to similar plateaus near 0.79--0.80.

