\begin{abstract}
We propose a method for interpretable neural rule learning in the Synthetic PolyRule Reasoning (SPR) task, which requires classification based on latent poly-factor rules. Existing neural and symbolic approaches either lack interpretability or rely on post-hoc methods that do not provide explicit rule representations. Our model is designed to learn and represent these rules in a human-readable format. We present experiments on the SPR\_BENCH dataset, focusing on classification accuracy and interpretable rule extraction. Results indicate that, while classification F1 scores approach 0.80, the learned rules capture partial dependencies underlying the task. We highlight trade-offs between performance and transparency, as well as potential overfitting when rule complexity is high.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
Practical applications of deep learning often involve complex reasoning and decision-making, where interpretability is critical \citep{goodfellow2016deep}. Neural rule learning aims to make learning models more transparent by discovering interpretable rule structures \citep{dong2019neurallm}. However, existing methods frequently rely on opaque high-dimensional embeddings \citep{barbiero2023interpretablenc}, or employ post-hoc explanation approaches that can be unreliable in representing actual decision mechanisms \citep{hooshyar2024problemsws}. We address the Synthetic PolyRule Reasoning (SPR) task, where classification requires understanding symbol sequences governed by multiple latent factors. We investigate whether it is feasible for a neural system to learn these rules explicitly, evaluating both performance and interpretability. This problem highlights a real-world pitfall: balancing model transparency with accuracy, especially under highly structured data regimes.

\section{Related Work}
Neural-symbolic systems combine sub-symbolic processing with discrete rule structures, allowing models to perform logical inference while retaining flexibility \citep{liu2024neuralsymbolicro}. Symbolic reasoning approaches, such as building explicit rule structures, promote interpretability but may sacrifice generalization \citep{barbiero2023interpretablenc}. Benchmark tasks like KOR-Bench \citep{ma2024korbenchbl} offer controlled evaluations of rule-based reasoning. In addition, supervised rule-based classifiers provide readable rules \citep{heider2020suprbas}, though neural networks typically embed rules only implicitly. We aim to integrate techniques from these lines of work and provide both clarity in rule representation and competitive performance. By explicitly reporting inconclusive or partially negative findings, we highlight the nuanced trade-offs in real deployment.

\section{Method}
We adopt a hybrid framework that combines a character-level encoder with a rule-based layer to produce explicit rules. A standard bi-directional recurrent encoder (or variant) transforms character sequences into hidden representations. In parallel, a lightweight linear rule extractor learns token-level importance weights that can be read as class-specific triggers. The final classification logit is the ensemble average of these two branches. We train using cross-entropy loss plus a small regularization term on the rule weights for interpretability. The Adam optimizer \citep{kingma2014adamam} is employed with a learning rate grid from $\{5\times10^{-4},7\times10^{-4},2\times10^{-3}\}$ and early stopping on validation F1.

\section{Experiments}
We evaluate on the SPR\_BENCH dataset with official splits using a Char-BiLSTM as our baseline. As shown in \cref{fig:baseline_valf1}, the baseline reaches \(\approx 0.79\)--\(0.80\) Macro F1 with multiple learning rates. This figure clearly illustrates how quickly the model converges in the early epochs, then saturates, indicating limited headroom for further gains through simple adjustments of training dynamics.

