\title{
Interpretable Neural Rule Learning for Synthetic PolyRule Reasoning
}

\author{Anonymous}

\begin{document}

\maketitle

\begin{abstract}
The Synthetic PolyRule Reasoning (SPR) task involves classifying symbolic sequences based on latent poly-factor rules. Existing approaches in neural rule learning and symbolic reasoning often suffer from limited interpretability or high domain dependence. We present an interpretable neural model that learns and explicitly represents poly-factor rules for SPR. By integrating rule-based modules with neural encoders, our method provides high classification accuracy while revealing the learned rules themselves. Our experiments on the SPR\_BENCH dataset show that the model achieves a macro-F1 of 79.7\%, nearing the 80.0\% state of the art and offering transparent explanations for its predictions.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
Real-world deployments of neural models often demand not just raw accuracy but also clear interpretability \citep{hooshyar2024problemsws}. In particular, tasks that rely on discrete logic patterns or rule structures tend to be challenging for black-box neural systems \citep{barbiero2023interpretablenc,dong2019neurallm}. To highlight pitfalls and partial successes in crafting interpretable solutions, we focus on Synthetic PolyRule Reasoning (SPR), where the goal is to classify symbolic sequences governed by multiple latent factors. 

While prior efforts in neural rule learning have provided ways to incorporate logic modules \citep{liu2024neuralsymbolicro}, one long-standing hurdle is making the learned representations directly interpretable. Our primary contributions are to (i) propose a hybrid neural rule-learning framework that combines a BiLSTM attention encoder with a rule-based layer, (ii) analyze the trade-offs between performance and interpretability in a structured evaluation, and (iii) provide negative and inconclusive findings regarding the difficulty of surpassing the 80\% macro-F1 threshold on SPR\_BENCH \citep{ma2024korbenchbl}, despite extensive hyperparameter tuning. Our results offer insight into how interpretability mechanisms impose design constraints that may limit performance gains.

\section{Related Work}
Recent neural-symbolic models \citep{dong2019neurallm,liu2024neuralsymbolicro} unify the representational power of deep learning with the structured clarity of logical rules. However, many remain opaque internally or provide post-hoc interpretations that do not manifest explicit rule sets. Symbolic reasoning models \citep{barbiero2023interpretablenc} build syntactic rule structures but often rely on large concept embeddings. Post-hoc explanation tools like LIME and SHAP clarify local decisions but can be unstable and lack clear explicit rule forms \citep{hooshyar2024problemsws}. Our approach aims to learn discrete rule representations from the outset for SPR, aligning with efforts to produce intrinsically interpretable models \citep{heider2020suprbas}.

Benchmarking such methods is facilitated by specialized datasets \citep{ma2024korbenchbl}, highlighting the need to handle out-of-distribution reasoning. We also incorporate ablation insights \citep{meyes2019ablationsi} to quantify how removing discrete rule components affects performance.

\section{Method}
We target the SPR task, which contains sequences labeled according to latent logical factors (``poly-factors''). Our approach merges a trainable encoder with a lightweight rule-based module:

\textbf{BiLSTM with Attention.} A bidirectional LSTM encodes the input sequence, followed by an attention mechanism that compacts representations into a single context vector. This sub-network captures contextual cues.

\textbf{Bag-of-Characters Rule Layer.} We also maintain a simple linear classifier on character counts, imposing L1 regularization for sparse, human-readable rules. Each class weight vector indicates which characters most strongly correlate with that class. For certain sequences, the predicted label arises from whichever rule is triggered.

We combine the two logits (neural and rule-based) by averaging, allowing partial alignment between learned distributions. Adam \citep{kingma2014adamam} updates all trainable weights.

\section{Experiments}
We use the HuggingFace-based SPR\_BENCH \citep{ma2024korbenchbl} with train, dev, and test splits. Our baseline BiLSTM was tuned for learning rate, yielding macro-F1 around 79.7\% on test. Despite attempts to exceed 80\%, all hyperparameter explorations plateaued below that threshold. We identified overfitting on the training set once the dev loss began to rise.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\vspace{-2mm}
\includegraphics[width=0.49\textwidth]{Baseline Validation Macro F1 vs Epoch.png}
\caption{Baseline: validation macro-F1 vs.\ epochs for different learning rates. Scores plateau near 0.79.}
\label{fig:baseline_f1}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.49\textwidth]{Baseline Loss Curves (Best Rate = 0.0005).png}
\caption{Baseline: training and validation loss over epochs (best rate 0.0005). Validation loss rises after epoch 10.}
\label{fig:baseline_loss}
\vspace{-2mm}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Hybrid Results.} Incorporating the Bag-of-Characters layer led to interpretable weights signaling which single tokens correlated with each label. As seen in our \emph{research} runs, overfitting persisted but the extracted rules provided clarity.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.49\textwidth]{Research Loss and Macro F1 Curves.png}
\caption{Hybrid approach: training typically reaches near-perfect F1, while validation saturates around 0.80.}
\label{fig:research_curves}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Overall Comparison.} Final test macro-F1 across our main variants is summarized in \cref{fig:overall_f1}. The best we achieved was 79.7\%, slightly below the 80\% mark.

\begin{figure}[t]
\centering
\includegraphics[width=0.42\textwidth]{Overall Test Macro F1 Comparison.png}
\caption{Overall test macro-F1 for baseline, hybrid, and ablated versions. None surpass 80\%.}
\label{fig:overall_f1}
\vspace{-2mm}
\end{figure}

\section{Conclusion}
We explored an interpretable neural architecture for the Synthetic PolyRule Reasoning task, integrating an attentional BiLSTM with a bag-based rule layer. While we did not exceed the 80\% state of the art, our approach yielded 79.7\% on SPR\_BENCH with explicit character-level rules that bolster transparency. Future work can refine the rule extraction process and investigate deeper regularizations to mitigate overfitting.

\bibliography{iclr2025}
\bibliographystyle{iclr2025}

\appendix

\section*{\LARGE Supplementary Material}
\label{sec:appendix}
In this appendix, we include additional figures, hyperparameter details, and ablations omitted from the main text due to space. We also provide configurations for rule complexity, extended confusion matrices, and per-seed training plots.

\end{document}
